arch:property.oc:show_val: L13 is soft ashy fill starting from the east baulk south of the wall L7. It extends almost to the west baulk. We changed to this locus when there was a clear distinction between the mudbrick collapse in L14 at the west baulk south of the wall and the ashy fill. L13 continues beneath L14 towards the west baulk. As we cleared the fill beside the wall we realized that we had passed the bottom of the wall and its foundations when we had reached a layer of ash that started at the south baulk and continued north past the wall in L7. Therefore the three ash layer loci are equal, L13 at the south side of the wall, L18 under the wall and L15 north of the wall.
very soft fine clayey loam ash layer
rocks, pottery, not much artifacts, mudbrick debris
this is the cleanest layer of ashy so far, there is less mudbrick debris, and the area is more uniform

arch:note.arch:string: Contexts excavated in trenches were recorded using the "locus system." A locus is any discrete three-dimensional entity excavated in a trench. The key to the locus system is the recognition that a locus is any one thing. Differences in soil composition or texture are therefore as important as, for example, the difference between a pit and a wall. If two entities were distinct, they were considered separate loci and were therefore assigned separate locus numbers. It should also be noted that every context excavated in a trench was given a locus number and thus the trench itself is made up completely of excavated loci.
